result.execSummary:
The defendant Dennis G Dupee Jr was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Theft-False Representation <=$2500 [Modifiers: Repeater], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.20(1)(d).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Reserve Judge Mawdsley presiding for Branch IV:  
[MK] case called at 11:40am. 
Defendant Dennis G Dupee in court, in custody, with Attorney John V Rhiel.  ADA Jeffrey Shock appears for the State of Wisconsin.  

Constitutional rights reviewed; maximum penalties recited; plea of "  Guilty " entered on Count #1; factual basis stipulated; victim rights compliance verified (ADA Shock submits the victim impact statement and restitution information); the Court accepts the plea, finds Mr. Dupee guilty, and orders Judgment of Conviction entered.

On Motion of the State, the Court reads-in and dismisses Count #2.

On Count #1, the Court sentences Mr. Dupee to 2 years, with an Initial Term of Confinement in Prison of 1  year, and the maximum time to serve on Extended Supervision of  1 year.  This sentence is consecutive to any sentence in being.
The Court finds that the Defendant is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program "Boot Camp".
The Court finds that the Defendant is not eligible for the Earned Release Program.
The Court gives 0 days credit for time already served.
